== *1. Skin mycobiome in prepubescent children and their mothers*
Human skin is permanently colonized by microbes starting at birth. The hygiene hypothesis suggests that a lack of early-life immune imprinting weakens the body’s resilience against atopic disorders later in life. To better understand fungal colonization following early-life periods affected by interruption, I studied the skin mycobiome of 73 prepubescent children (≤ 10-year-old) and their mothers. 
\n

+This research has been published in /*Microbiology Spectrum*/\ (DOI: [https://journals.asm.org/doi/10.1128/spectrum.02267-22 10.1128\/spectrum.02267-22]).+ 
Analysis results (Figure 1.1) suggest differentiation of the skin mycobiome between caesarean-born and vaginally-born children. 
Caesarean-born children exhibit a mycobiome structure with more fitted deterministic niche-based processes, a fragile network, and an unchanged microbial dissimilarity over time. 
In vaginally-born children, this dissimilarity increases with age. 
Additionally, the mycobiome of vaginally-born children at younger ages are more strongly correlated with vagina-associated fungal genera (/Candida/\ and /Rhodotorula/\, Figure 1.2), whereas those of caesarean-delivered children at elder age include more skin-associated and airborne fungal genera (/Malassezia/\ and /Alternaria/\).
