== *4. Culture and genome analysis of autotrophic nitrifying bacteria*
Nitrification, consisting of two processes: ammonia oxidation (oxidizing ammonia to nitrite as mentioned above in AOA) and nitrification (oxidizing nitrite to nitrate), was for a long time assumed to be catalyzed by distinct guilds of chemolithoautotrophic microorganisms. However, in 2015, the discovery of complete ammonia-oxidizing (comammox) /Nitrospira/\ has added an important new process to the microbial nitrogen cycle.
\n\n
In my current lab (Supervisor: /[https://scholar.google.com/citations?user=Yu1liDUAAAAJ&hl=en&oi=ao/ Professor Zhe-Xue Quan]/\), there are several enrichments of comammox derived from distinct environments (including activated sludge, tap water, paddy soil and salt marsh, Figure 4.1); and I have been responsible for the cultivation and weekly detection of bacterial activity, NGS data analysis (including the type of amplicon and shotgun), genome assembly/binning and genome annotation analysis of these 3 comammox cultures (except the comammox from tap water).
~~~
{}{img_center}{photos/Figure_bottles.jpeg}{alttext}{60%}{}{}
*Figure 4.1* Comammox /Nitrospira/\ enrichments from different environments in Schott bottles.
~~~

Since these comammox enrichments often have comammox /Nitrospira/\ and canonical /Nitrospira/\ simultaneously, their affinity in sequences would make it tricky to obtain targeted comammox /Nitrospira/\ genomes even with a higher abundance. Here I have improved this process by various methods: hybrid asssembly of nanopore and NGS data, subsetting of NGS data for reducing the impact of low-abundance canonical /Nitrospira/\ species, new method of long-read sequencing – [https://www.universalsequencing.com/technology TELL-Seq], some of which greatly improved the completeness and quality of MAG (Figure 4.2).
~~~
{}{img_center}{photos/Table.png}{alttext}{95%}{}{}
*Figure 4.2* General genomic features of the high-quality comammox /Nitrospira/\ genomes reconstructed from assembly.
~~~

Additionally, I am also cultivating enrichments of a novel type of ammonia-oxidizing bacteria (AOB) from mudflat soils in the lab and trying to obtain its high-quality genome. By reviewing the literature, I have designed several routes to try to obtain enrichments of AOB with higher abundance percentages, and the experiments are still in progress. 
This will be followed up with a simultaneous global distribution analysis of this AOB for environmental samples in the SRA database -- to determine the upper limit of the potential value of this study.

== *5. Rapid detection of /Cronobacter sakazakii/\ *
During my undergraduate years, I successfully applied for an Innovation and Entrepreneurship project national that was established as a national project (¥10,000), 
which is mainly based on fluorescence labelling and rolling circle amplification (RCA) to achieve the rapid detection of /Cronobacter Sakazakii/\ – a typical pathogenic bacteria in milk powder.
\n\n
In the first stage of the experiment, the sample of no template control (NTC) showed a positive result in RCA, which was solved by modificating the condition of different primer concentrations after consulting related research papers.
As the problem of NTC has been controlled (Figure 5.1.A), furthermore, I applied SYBR Green I into RCA detection mixtures and successfully achieved visual detection of genomic DNA extracted from /Cronobacter Sakazakii/\ under UV light (Figure 5.1.B). 
However, limited time was left before my graduation due to the quarantine brought on by COVID--19 pandemic, so I chose to publish a review paper (in Chinese) to accomplish the project. 
Through this earliest project in my research of life science, personally, what I gain is not only the experiment skills but also the way to solve actual problems in the project.
~~~
